<div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark"><p data-start="0" data-end="85" class="">Sure! Here's a <strong data-start="15" data-end="57">short, clear note on Simpson's Paradox</strong>, great for quick reference:</p>
<hr data-start="87" data-end="90" class="" style="">
<h2 data-start="92" data-end="138" class="">ðŸŒ€ <strong data-start="98" data-end="119">Simpson's Paradox</strong> â€“ Explained Simply</h2>
<h3 data-start="140" data-end="164" class="">ðŸ“Œ <strong data-start="147" data-end="162">What is it?</strong></h3>
<p data-start="165" data-end="319" class=""><strong data-start="165" data-end="186">Simpsonâ€™s Paradox</strong> is a phenomenon in statistics where a trend appears in <strong data-start="242" data-end="268">several groups of data</strong> but <strong data-start="273" data-end="285">reverses</strong> whens are <strong data-start="306" data-end="318">combined</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="321" data-end="324" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="326" data-end="358" class="">ðŸ§  <strong data-start="333" data-end="356">Why does it happen?</strong></h3>
<p data-start="359" data-end="509" class="">Because of the influence of a <strong data-start="389" data-end="409">lurking variable</strong> (also called a <strong data-start="425" data-end="449">confounding variable</strong>) that skews the overall data when you aggregate the groups.</p>
<hr data-start="511" data-end="514" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="516" data-end="540" class="">ðŸŽ¯ <strong data-start="523" data-end="538">Key Insight</strong></h3>
<blockquote data-start="541" data-end="619">
<p data-start="543" data-end="619" class=""><strong data-start="543" data-end="601">Aggregated data can hide or even reverse real patterns</strong> in the subgroups.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr data-start="621" data-end="624" class="" style="">
